1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. Bxb8 ({Nowadays} 3. e3 {is most frequently played.}) 3...
Rxb8 4. dxc5 {The great German chess teacher Dr. Tarrasch certainly would have
critisized White's play. Exchanging a developed bishop for an inactive knight
and giving up the centre - can this be good? But we know that it is not the
single move itself, but the plan behind it which counts. If you have a good
one, you can play almost everything.} Qa5+ ({Beware, a trap!} 4... e6 $1 5. Qd4
(5. e3 {is better}) 5... Qc7 6. b4 $2 b6 $1 7. cxb6 Rxb6 8. c3 $2 (8. a3 $1)
8... Rxb4 $1 9. cxb4 $2 Qc1+ 10. Qd1 Bxb4+ 11. Nd2 Bxd2#) 5. Nc3 e6 (5... Qxc5
$2 6. Qxd5) 6. e4 ({Rb8 is undefended. This is why Black must be careful as we
can learn from some of the following variations:} 6. a3 $5 Qxc5 (6... Bxc5 $2
7. b4) 7. e4 d4 8. Nb5 e5 9. c3 $1 Bd7 (9... a6 $2 10. cxd4 Qb6 11. Qh5 $1 axb5
$2 12. Qxe5+ Kd8 13. Qxb8 Bd6 14. Qa8 $18) (9... dxc3 10. Rc1 $1 Bg4 11. Nf3 $1
(11. Qxg4 $2 cxb2 $1) 11... Bxf3 12. gxf3 (12. Qxf3 $2 cxb2 $1) 12... Rd8 13.
Bd3 Qb6 14. Rxc3 Be7 15. Nc7+ Kf8 16. Nd5 Qxb2 17. Rb3 Qd4 ({after} 17... Qa2
$2 18. Nc3 {the black queen is trapped}) 18. Rxb7 $14) 10. cxd4 Qb6 11. Qh5 ({
perhaps even} 11. Qb3 $5 a6 12. Bc4 Bxb5 13. Bxf7+ {is playable}) 11... Bxb5 $2
(11... Rc8) 12. Qxe5+ {winning Rb8 and one of Black's bishops.}) 6... Bxc5 (
6... dxe4 $2 {leads to a quick defeat after} 7. Bb5+ Ke7 8. Qd6+) 7. exd5 Nf6 (
7... Ba3 $5 8. Bb5+ Kf8 9. Qc1 $13) 8. Bb5+ Ke7 (8... Bd7 $2 9. Bxd7+ Nxd7 10.
dxe6 fxe6 11. Qh5+ g6 12. Qe2 $16) 9. Nf3 (9. dxe6 {is not so good} Bb4 $1 10.
Bd3 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qxc3+ 12. Kf1 Bxe6 13. Ne2 Qc5 $15 {
Rh1 is locked in, while Rh8 can easily be brought into play.}) 9... Nxd5 (9...
Bb4 $5 10. d6+ $1 Bxd6 11. O-O Rd8 12. Qe2 $11) ({A tempting move is} 9... Ne4
{, but after} 10. Qd3 $1 {neither N nor B can advantageously take the pawn:}
Nxf2 $2 (10... Bxf2+ $2 11. Kf1 $1 Nxc3 12. d6+ Kf8 13. d7 $1 $16) (10... Nxc3
$1 11. bxc3 Rd8 12. Bc4 exd5 13. Bb3 Kf8 14. O-O $1 $11 (14. Qxh7 $2 Qxc3+))
11. d6+ $1 Kf8 (11... Kf6 $2 12. Qd2 $1 $18) 12. Qc4 Nxh1 (12... Qb6 13. Rf1
$18) 13. Qxc5 {threatening d7+} Kg8 14. O-O-O $18) 10. Qd2 $1 Nxc3 $2 {
This move looks good at first sight, but in reality it is a blunder. Chigorin
either overlooked White's next move or miscalculated the resulting variations.}
(10... Bb4 {could have been played, e.g.} 11. Qg5+ ({or} 11. Nxd5+ exd5 12. c3
Qxb5 $1 13. Qg5+ Kf8 14. Qd8+ Qe8+ 15. Qxe8+ Kxe8 16. cxb4 $11) 11... Kf8 12.
O-O $1 Bxc3 ({after} 12... Nxc3 13. bxc3 Bxc3 14. Qc5+ Kg8 15. Qe7 $1 h6 16.
Rab1 {White's positional advantage is worth more than a pawn} Qxa2 $2 {
must not be played on account of} 17. Qc7 $1 {attacking both Rc7 and Bc3}) 13.
bxc3 f6 (13... Qxb5 $2 14. Qd8+ Qe8 15. Qd6+ {
and again the undefended Rb8 gets lost}) 14. Qg3 (14. Qh4 $5 {intending} Qxb5
15. c4 {might be preferable}) 14... Qc7 $1 {Black's development is still
lagging behind, but he has a better pawn structure.}) 11. Qg5+ $1 f6 $2 (11...
Kd6 $2 12. Qe5+ $1 Ke7 13. Qxc5+ Kd8 14. Qd6+ Bd7 15. Qxd7#) ({
Maybe Chigorin had calculated} 11... Kf8 12. Qxc5+ Kg8 13. bxc3 a6 {
and noticed too late that White can save his Bb5 by playing} 14. Qe5 {
now Qe5 is protected by Nf3, Rb8 attacked and Bb5 no longer pinned. But} axb5 {
does not help either because of} 15. Qxb8 Qxc3+ 16. Kd1 {
and the black queen has only one more check, but this one loses right off}
Qxa1+ $2 17. Kd2 $1 Qxh1 18. Qxc8#) 12. Qxc5+ ({This move is better than} 12.
Qxg7+) 12... Kf7 (12... Kd8 13. Qd6+ Bd7 14. Qxd7#) 13. Be8+ $1 {
and Chigorin resigned, because after} Rxe8 14. Qxa5 {his queen is lost.} 1-0

